# No Backwards Compatibility By Default

This is a greenfield project. There are no external consumers to protect, no
agents that depend on stable APIs yet, and the schema in `~/.pier/projects.json`
can be migrated freely. Backwards compatibility is almost always wrong here —
it's usually an excuse to avoid chasing down callers.

When changing an API, function signature, data shape, CLI flag, or behavior:

- Update every call site in the same change. Don't leave the old path alive.
- Delete now-unused options, helpers, branches, and dead code.
- Update CLI help text, tray menu labels, GUI labels, `README.md`, and
  `agent-skill/SKILL.md` to match the new reality.
- Migrate the on-disk config (`~/.pier/projects.json`) in `migrateProject` if
  the field rename / removal needs it. Don't keep accepting the old shape.

Do NOT introduce, without explicit user permission:

- `options.legacy`, `options.compat`, `options.all`-style dual-mode flags
  used solely to preserve old behavior
- Deprecation warnings or "if old shape, do old thing" branches
- Wrapper functions whose only purpose is to forward to the new API in the
  old format
- "Backwards-compatible" defaults that re-create the previous behavior

If preserving an old behavior genuinely matters in a specific case, ASK FIRST.
The default answer is to break and fix.
